	<title>Exercises: Cross Product Theory</title>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Show that, for arbitrary vectors <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>, any scalar multiple <latex>t\cdot (\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} })</latex> of the cross product is perpendicular to both <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Show that, for arbitrary vectors <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>, <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>, and <latex>\Vect{w}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>,</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\DotPr{ (\Vect{u} + \Vect{v} ) }{( \CrssPr{(\Vect{u} + \Vect{v})}{ \Vect{w} }) }</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>0</right>
			</computation>
		</problem>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Show that, for arbitrary vectors <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>, <latex>\Vect{v}</latex>, and <latex>\Vect{w}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>,</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\DotPr{ \Vect{u} }{ (\CrssPr{ \Vect{v} }{ \Vect{w} }) }</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>-\DotPr{ \Vect{v} }{ (\CrssPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{w} }) }</right>
			</computation>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<solution.hint>
				<para>Recall the formula which relates dot product, cross product, and determinant:</para>
				<computation>
					<left>\DotPr{ \Vect{u} }{ (\CrssPr{ \Vect{v} }{ \Vect{w} }) }</left>
					<center>=</center>
					<right>\det[\Vect{u}\ \ \Vect{v}\ \ \Vect{w}]</right>
				</computation>
			</solution.hint>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>If <latex>\Vect{a}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{b}</latex> are orthonormal vectors in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> which lie in a hyperspace <latex>H</latex>, show that <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{a} }{ \Vect{b} }</latex> is a unit normal vector of <latex>H</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
	</exercise>
